Sure! Below is a simple Java program that implements the bubble sort algorithm to sort an array of integers in ascending order.

```java
public class BubbleSort {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] array = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
        bubbleSort(array);
        System.out.println("Sorted array in ascending order:");
        printArray(array);
    }

    // Method to perform bubble sort
    public static void bubbleSort(int[] array) {
        int n = array.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++) {
                if (array[j] > array[j+1]) {
                    // swap array[j+1] and array[j]
                    int temp = array[j];
                    array[j] = array[j+1];
                    array[j+1] = temp;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // Method to print the array
    public static void printArray(int[] array) {
        for (int i : array) {
            System.out.print(i + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();
    }
}
```

### Explanation:

1. **bubbleSort Method:**
   - This method takes an array of integers as input and sorts it using the bubble sort algorithm.
   - It uses two nested loops:
     - The outer loop runs from the first element to the second-to-last element.
     - The inner loop compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are in the wrong order.
   - This process repeats until the entire array is sorted.

2. **printArray Method:**
   - This method is used to print the elements of the array.
   - It iterates through the array and prints each element.

3. **main Method:**
   - This is the entry point of the program.
   - It initializes an array with some integers.
   - Calls the `bubbleSort` method to sort the array.
   - Prints the sorted array using the `printArray` method.

This program demonstrates a basic implementation of the bubble sort algorithm in Java. Bubble sort is simple but not efficient for large datasets due to its O(n^2) time complexity. For larger datasets, more efficient sorting algorithms like quicksort or mergesort are preferred.
